thread.title: UA football has reasons for concern, optimism
thread.title_full: UA football has reasons for concern, optimism

author: azcentral.com
title: UA football has reasons for concern, optimism
text:
BOULDER, Colo. — As Rich Rodriguez walked to the team bus late Saturday night, someone from afar blurted out a question.
“Did you see what Michigan State did to Michigan?”
Rodriguez turned around, smiled, and said, “No I didn’t, but I heard it was crazy.”
Just before Arizona took Folsom Field for its game — and eventual 38-31 win against Colorado — Michigan lost on a wild last-second play. The Spartans recovered a botched Wolverines punt and scored a game-ending touchdown as time expired.
Rodriguez was fired by Michigan in 2010 after just three seasons, so any time something happens to Michigan, someone tends to mention it to the Wildcats' coach.
AZCENTRAL
UA football pulls away from Colorado in road victory
By the time Rodriguez left the stadium, hopped onto the bus, and walked onto Arizona’s charter flight back to Tucson, he probably had forgotten about the Michigan game — if he even cared about it in the first place.
Arizona has problems of its own, particularly on defense.
Injuries and suspensions have decimated Arizona’s depth. It’s why Jace Whittaker, a freshman, started at cornerback for the first time and Jack Banda, an undersized, 228-pound defensive end, played the most snaps of his career.
“I thought we gave up too much easy stuff in the secondary, it was frustrating a little bit,” Rodriguez said.
Colorado gained nearly 500 total yards of offense, many of them in the first quarter; the Buffaloes led 24-17 heading into the fourth quarter.
AZCENTRAL
Wildcats’ ‘second season’ begins with winnable game
All of that was the bad. But it’s not all bad — Arizona (5-2, 2-2 Pac-12) is one win away from bowl eligibility, after all — and there’s some reason for optimism going forward.
And that starts with Rodriguez, and Arizona’s offense.
With so many moving parts this season, more than ever Rodriguez has become something of a mad scientist, and it seems to be working.
Consider: Only six of Arizona’s 11 offensive starters have started every game this season. They are offensive linemen Cayman Bundage, Jacob Alsadek and Lene Maiava, and receivers Cayleb Jones, Nate Phillips and David Richards.
Arizona's offense has reason for optimism going forward as it prepares for this week's game against Washington State. Here are three reasons why.

You may also like these photo galleries: Replay Autoplay Show Thumbnails Show Captions Last Slide Next Slide They’re getting healthy: Running back Nick Wilson missed Saturday’s game with a foot injury, but might be ready to go for Washington State.
Wilson notwithstanding, Arizona is finally getting everybody back. Anu Solomon missed most of UCLA and all of the Stanford game with a concussion, but returned to face Oregon State. Tyrell Johnson, a running back-receiver hybrid, joined him.
Receiver Trey Griffey made his season debut against Colorado after missing the previous six games with a foot injury.
The full arsenal was on display Saturday — Solomon completed at least one pass to seven different receivers to start the game. He found tight end Josh Kern for a rare touchdown pass.
AZCENTRAL
Arizona Wildcats XTRA app: Get latest news, scores
The rushing attack: In Wilson’s absence, Jared Baker had the game of his life. The fifth-year senior rushed for 207 yards and two scores against Colorado, and has 330 yards over the last two games. Baker has 60 carries this season, 33 more than his previous season high.
“Jared’s a veteran: he runs hard, and he’s one of the fastest guys we’ve got," Rodriguez said. "I think you saw that in a couple of runs.”
Randall’s athleticism helped open up some running lanes for Baker. The Wildcats' backup quarterback had 81 rushing yards Saturday, and has 534 this year.
“I got in and Jared started running the ball,” Randall said. “They started to account for me, and it was like three guys looking at me, not paying attention to Jared and he was running down the field for 50.”
The Wildcats are averaging 297.4 rushing yards per game, tied for sixth-best in the nation, and are on pace to break a 61-year old team record. Arizona has 14 rushing plays of 30-plus yards this season, and is tied with Georgia Southern for the most in college football this season.
AZCENTRAL
UA football turning to backup RBs
Rodriguez’s mind: When quarterback B.J. Denker had a few troubled nights back in 2013, Rodriguez kept the lefty in the lineup.
It had been the same for Solomon until Saturday, when — with Arizona's offense sputtering — Rodriguez benched the sophomore for ineffectiveness. It wound up being a game-changing move, and Randall guided the Wildcats to victory.
"It definitely helps when you got a guy who can run as fast as he can," Baker said. "He’s a threat that definitely opens up lanes."
Rodriguez continues to tinker with the Wildcats' offense.
He inserted Layth Friekh at left tackle against Oregon State, and moved Freddie Tagaloa to left guard; in the preseason he brought Jamardre Cobb and Johnny Jackson over from the defensive side of the ball to play key roles at fullback and receiver, respectively.
Rodriguez displayed some old-school trickery late in Saturday's game, deploying a running back wheel route play in the fourth quarter that led to a 25-yard touchdown catch by Baker.
“We had used it before, it’s kind of a one-time-per-game” play, Rodriguez said. “They actually blitzed and played 'zero' coverage and lost sight of the back. Jared bobbled it a bit, but it was much-needed for sure.”
